url.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTo a degree uncommon in among Chinese cities, Republican Shanghai had no center. Its territory was divided among three (sometimes more) municipal governments integrated into various national states and empires. No government building or religious institution gave Shanghai a “center." Yet amidst deep cleavages, the city functioned as a coherent whole. What held Shanghai together? The authors' answer is that a group of middlemen with myriad connections across political and social boundaries created networks that held Republican Shanghai together. Contributors Include: Sei Jeong Chin, Parks Coble, Bryna Goodman, Brian Martin, Elizabeth J. Perry, Kuiyi Shen, Jeffrey Wasserstrom, and Wen-hsin Yeh  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aCultural pluralismzChinazShanghaixHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial networkszChinazShanghaixHistoryy20th century. 4aAsian Studies. 4aHistory -- Asian. 4aPolitics -- Asia. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aChin, Sei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoble, Parks, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDillon, Nara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDillon, Nara, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoodman, Bryna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOi, Jean C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOi, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerry, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShen, Kuiyi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWasserstro